    "summary": "The House of Wisdom (Bayt al-Hikma, established c. 830 AD under Caliph al-Mamun in [[event:2134|Baghdad]]) was the greatest library and research institution of the medieval world — a state-funded center for translation, scholarship, and original research that gathered manuscripts from Greece, Persia, India, and across the Islamic world, translated them into Arabic, and served as the hub of the [[event:2135|Islamic Golden Age's]] intellectual production. Under al-Mamun, who paid translators by the weight of gold equal to their manuscripts, the House of Wisdom became the focal point of an unprecedented translation movement.\n\nThe translations produced at the House of Wisdom saved much of the Greek intellectual tradition that would otherwise have been lost: works of Aristotle, Plato, Hippocrates, Galen, Euclid, Ptolemy, Archimedes, and dozens of other Greek authors were translated into Arabic, often via Syriac intermediaries. These Arabic translations later formed the basis for the Latin translations that transmitted Greek philosophy and science to medieval Europe — meaning that the House of Wisdom is a crucial link in the chain connecting ancient Greek thought to the European Renaissance. Original scholarship at the institution included [[event:2137|al-Khwarizmi's]] mathematical works, astronomical tables, and geographic treatises. The House of Wisdom was destroyed when Mongols sacked Baghdad in 1258, reportedly throwing so many books into the Tigris that the river ran black with ink — one of history's most catastrophic losses of written knowledge.",
